  qs:[
    {q:"Your service's response time degraded from 100ms to 500ms. Walk through your debugging process.",d:"hard",
     a:"This is a systematic approach to diagnosing performance degradation in production.<br><br><strong>Step 1 — Confirm the symptom with metrics:</strong><br>Check Grafana/Datadog:<ul><li>p50, p95, p99 latency (which percentile degraded?)</li><li>Request rate (did traffic increase?)</li><li>Error rate (are errors causing slowness?)</li></ul><br><strong>Step 2 — Correlate with timeline:</strong><ul><li>When did degradation start? (deployment? config change?)</li><li>Check <code>kubectl rollout history</code> or git commits</li><li>Any infrastructure changes? (database upgrade, network)</li></ul><br><strong>Step 3 — Check distributed traces:</strong><br>Query Jaeger/Tempo for slow requests:<pre>service=order-service\nlatency &gt; 400ms\ntime=[degradation start time]</pre>Examine trace spans to identify bottleneck:<ul><li>Is it the app code? (CPU-bound computation)</li><li>Database queries? (slow SQL, connection pool exhausted)</li><li>External APIs? (payment gateway, third-party service)</li><li>Network latency? (cross-region calls)</li></ul><br><strong>Step 4 — Profile the application (if code is the bottleneck):</strong><br><pre># Enable JFR (Java Flight Recorder)\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.start duration=60s filename=profile.jfr\n\n# Or use async-profiler\n./profiler.sh -d 60 -f /tmp/flamegraph.html &lt;pid&gt;</pre>Analyze flame graph:<ul><li>Which methods consume the most CPU?</li><li>Is there a new code path that's slow?</li><li>Excessive object allocation?</li></ul><br><strong>Step 5 — Check JVM metrics:</strong><br><pre>jstat -gc &lt;pid&gt; 1000  # GC stats every 1s</pre><ul><li><strong>High GC time?</strong> → heap pressure, tune GC</li><li><strong>High full GC frequency?</strong> → memory leak or undersized heap</li><li><strong>Thread contention?</strong> → check thread dumps</li></ul><br><strong>Step 6 — Database performance:</strong><br><pre># PostgreSQL slow queries\nSELECT query, mean_exec_time, calls\nFROM pg_stat_statements\nWHERE mean_exec_time &gt; 100\nORDER BY mean_exec_time DESC;</pre><ul><li>Missing indexes? <code>EXPLAIN ANALYZE</code></li><li>Table bloat? <code>VACUUM</code> needed?</li><li>Connection pool exhausted? (HikariCP metrics)</li></ul><br><strong>Step 7 — Check resource saturation:</strong><br><pre>top  # CPU usage per process\niostat -x 1  # disk I/O\nnetstat -s  # network errors</pre><ul><li>CPU at 100%? → CPU-bound code</li><li>Disk I/O wait high? → slow disk or swap thrashing</li><li>Network retransmissions? → packet loss</li></ul><br><strong>Step 8 — Thread dump analysis (if CPU is stuck):</strong><br><pre>jstack &lt;pid&gt; &gt; thread-dump.txt</pre>Look for:<ul><li>Threads blocked on locks</li><li>Deadlocks (jstack will report them)</li><li>Threads stuck in I/O (reading from slow external service)</li></ul><br><strong>Common root causes:</strong><ol><li><strong>Code regression:</strong> new code introduced inefficiency (N+1 query, bad algorithm)</li><li><strong>Increased traffic:</strong> system at capacity, need to scale</li><li><strong>Database slowdown:</strong> missing index, table lock, replication lag</li><li><strong>External dependency:</strong> third-party API degraded</li><li><strong>Memory leak:</strong> heap fills up → frequent GC → slow app</li><li><strong>Thread starvation:</strong> thread pool exhausted, requests queued</li></ol>"},

    {q:"Explain the trade-offs between throughput and latency in GC tuning.",d:"hard",
     a:"<strong>Throughput</strong> and <strong>latency</strong> are competing goals in garbage collection — optimizing one often degrades the other.<br><br><strong>Throughput:</strong><ul><li>Percentage of time spent on application work (not GC)</li><li>Example: 95% throughput = 5% time spent on GC</li><li>Goal: maximize useful work, minimize GC overhead</li></ul><br><strong>Latency (pause time):</strong><ul><li>Time the application is paused during GC</li><li>Example: p99 GC pause = 50ms</li><li>Goal: minimize pauses for responsive applications</li></ul><br><br><strong>The trade-off:</strong><br><br><strong>High throughput (batch processing, analytics):</strong><br>Use <strong>Parallel GC</strong> (<code>-XX:+UseParallelGC</code>):<ul><li>Optimizes for total throughput (~99%)</li><li>Long GC pauses (100ms - 1s) acceptable</li><li>Uses all CPU cores for GC (fast collection)</li><li>Simple, predictable, low overhead</li></ul><pre>-XX:+UseParallelGC\n-Xms4g -Xmx4g\n-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=500  # hint, not guarantee</pre><br><strong>Low latency (real-time, user-facing APIs):</strong><br>Use <strong>G1GC</strong> (<code>-XX:+UseG1GC</code>, default since Java 9) or <strong>ZGC</strong>:<ul><li>Optimizes for predictable, short pauses (&lt; 10ms)</li><li>Slightly lower throughput (95-97%)</li><li>Concurrent GC (runs alongside application)</li><li>More complex, higher CPU overhead</li></ul><pre>-XX:+UseG1GC\n-Xms4g -Xmx4g\n-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=20  # target 20ms pauses</pre><br><strong>Ultra-low latency (&lt; 10ms pauses):</strong><br>Use <strong>ZGC</strong> (<code>-XX:+UseZGC</code>) or <strong>Shenandoah</strong>:<ul><li>Sub-millisecond pauses (&lt; 1ms typical)</li><li>Works with huge heaps (TB+)</li><li>Even lower throughput (90-95%)</li><li>Higher memory overhead</li></ul><pre>-XX:+UseZGC\n-Xms16g -Xmx16g</pre><br><br><strong>Why you can't have both:</strong><ol><li><strong>Stop-the-world vs concurrent:</strong> STW GC is faster but pauses app; concurrent GC doesn't pause but uses CPU</li><li><strong>GC work vs app work:</strong> more frequent, shorter pauses = more total GC work = lower throughput</li><li><strong>Memory overhead:</strong> low-latency GCs need extra memory for concurrent marking</li></ol><br><strong>Example trade-off:</strong><br><table><tr><th>GC</th><th>Throughput</th><th>p99 Pause</th><th>Use Case</th></tr><tr><td>Parallel GC</td><td>99%</td><td>500ms</td><td>Batch jobs</td></tr><tr><td>G1GC</td><td>96%</td><td>20ms</td><td>APIs, web apps</td></tr><tr><td>ZGC</td><td>92%</td><td>&lt;1ms</td><td>Trading systems</td></tr></table><br><strong>Decision framework:</strong><ul><li><strong>Batch processing, analytics:</strong> maximize throughput (Parallel GC)</li><li><strong>Web APIs, microservices:</strong> balance throughput and latency (G1GC)</li><li><strong>Real-time, financial, gaming:</strong> minimize latency (ZGC/Shenandoah)</li></ul><br><strong>Tuning tip:</strong> Start with G1GC and <code>MaxGCPauseMillis=50</code>. Only switch to ZGC if G1 can't meet SLOs."},

    {q:"How would you identify a memory leak in a long-running Java application?",d:"hard",
     a:"<strong>Symptoms of a memory leak:</strong><ul><li>Heap usage grows continuously over days/weeks</li><li>Frequent full GCs (but heap doesn't shrink much)</li><li>Eventually: <code>OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space</code></li><li>Application restart temporarily fixes it</li></ul><br><br><strong>Step 1 — Confirm it's a leak (not just high memory usage):</strong><br>Monitor heap usage over time (Grafana, Datadog):<br><pre>jstat -gc &lt;pid&gt; 60000  # every 60s</pre>Look at old generation (OU = old space used):<ul><li><strong>Normal:</strong> OU increases, then drops after full GC</li><li><strong>Leak:</strong> OU increases after each full GC (sawtooth pattern trending up)</li></ul><br><strong>Step 2 — Capture heap dumps:</strong><br><pre># Manual heap dump\njmap -dump:live,format=b,file=/tmp/heap-dump.hprof &lt;pid&gt;\n\n# Automatic on OOM\n-XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError\n-XX:HeapDumpPath=/var/log/heapdumps/</pre><br><strong>Step 3 — Analyze with Eclipse MAT (Memory Analyzer Tool):</strong><br><pre># Download from eclipse.org/mat\n# Open heap-dump.hprof</pre><br><strong>MAT analysis workflow:</strong><br><br><strong>A. Leak Suspects Report (automatic):</strong><br>MAT auto-detects objects consuming most memory:<ul><li>Shows classes with large retained size</li><li>Identifies potential leak suspects</li></ul><br><strong>B. Histogram view:</strong><br>Shows object counts by class:<pre>Class Name                    | Objects | Shallow Heap | Retained Heap\n------------------------------|---------|--------------|---------------\ncom.example.User              | 1.2M    | 96 MB        | 450 MB\njava.util.HashMap$Node        | 5.6M    | 180 MB       | 320 MB\nchar[]                        | 3.8M    | 220 MB       | 220 MB</pre>Look for:<ul><li>Unexpectedly high object counts</li><li>Application classes dominating the heap</li></ul><br><strong>C. Dominator Tree:</strong><br>Shows which objects hold references to large object graphs:<ul><li>Helps find the \"root cause\" object preventing GC</li></ul><br><strong>D. Path to GC Roots:</strong><br>Right-click suspicious object → \"Path to GC Roots\" → \"exclude weak refs\"<br>Shows why the object isn't garbage collected:<pre>GC Root: Thread \"http-nio-8080-exec-15\"\n  → com.example.CacheManager (field: userCache)\n    → java.util.HashMap (field: table)\n      → HashMap$Node (field: value)\n        → com.example.User (1.2M instances)</pre><br><strong>Common leak patterns:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Unbounded cache (no eviction):</strong><br><pre>// Leak: cache grows forever\nprivate static Map&lt;String, User&gt; cache = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();</pre>Fix: use <code>Caffeine</code> or <code>Guava Cache</code> with size/time limits.<br><br><strong>2. Listeners not removed:</strong><br><pre>// Leak: listener holds reference to large object\npublicationService.addListener(this);\n// Forgot to call removeListener()</pre>Fix: always unregister in cleanup.<br><br><strong>3. ThreadLocal not cleaned:</strong><br><pre>// Leak: thread pool reuses threads, ThreadLocal accumulates\nprivate static ThreadLocal&lt;Context&gt; context = new ThreadLocal&lt;&gt;();</pre>Fix: call <code>context.remove()</code> after request.<br><br><strong>4. Static collections:</strong><br><pre>// Leak: static field lives forever\nprivate static List&lt;Order&gt; allOrders = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</pre>Fix: use weak references or bounded collections.<br><br><strong>Step 4 — Reproduce locally:</strong><br>Write a load test that triggers the leak faster:<pre>// Simulate production load for 10 minutes\nfor (int i = 0; i &lt; 100000; i++) {\n  myService.processRequest(...);\n}</pre><br><strong>Step 5 — Fix and verify:</strong><ul><li>Deploy fix</li><li>Monitor heap usage for 1-2 weeks</li><li>Verify old gen no longer grows indefinitely</li></ul>"},

    {q:"When would you choose ZGC over G1GC for a microservice?",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>ZGC</strong> (Z Garbage Collector) is designed for ultra-low latency (&lt; 10ms pauses) with large heaps, while <strong>G1GC</strong> balances latency and throughput.<br><br><strong>G1GC (Garbage-First, default since Java 9):</strong><ul><li><strong>Target:</strong> predictable pause times (10-200ms)</li><li><strong>Heap size:</strong> works well up to 32GB</li><li><strong>Pause time:</strong> ~10-50ms typical (p99)</li><li><strong>Throughput:</strong> 95-97%</li><li><strong>Tuning:</strong> <code>-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=50</code></li></ul><br><strong>ZGC (since Java 15):</strong><ul><li><strong>Target:</strong> ultra-low latency (&lt; 1ms pauses)</li><li><strong>Heap size:</strong> scales to multi-TB heaps</li><li><strong>Pause time:</strong> &lt; 1ms (sub-millisecond)</li><li><strong>Throughput:</strong> 90-95% (slightly lower than G1)</li><li><strong>Tuning:</strong> mostly auto-tuning</li></ul><br><br><strong>When to choose ZGC:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Strict latency SLOs (p99 &lt; 10ms):</strong><br>If your service has SLO: \"p99 latency &lt; 10ms\", G1GC pauses (10-50ms) will violate it.<pre># G1GC might cause 20ms pauses occasionally\n→ p99 latency = 25ms (violates SLO)\n\n# ZGC keeps pauses &lt; 1ms\n→ p99 latency = 8ms (meets SLO)</pre><br><strong>2. Large heap (16GB+):</strong><br>G1GC pause times increase with heap size. ZGC is constant:<pre># 32GB heap\nG1GC: 50-100ms pauses\nZGC: &lt; 1ms pauses (heap size independent)</pre><br><strong>3. Real-time systems:</strong><ul><li>Trading platforms (low-latency orders)</li><li>Gaming servers (consistent frame rates)</li><li>Media streaming (no buffering spikes)</li></ul><br><strong>4. High allocation rate with large heap:</strong><br>If your app allocates objects rapidly and needs a large heap, ZGC handles it without long pauses.<br><br><strong>When to stick with G1GC:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Latency SLO is relaxed (p99 &lt; 50ms):</strong><br>G1GC's 10-20ms pauses are acceptable.<br><br><strong>2. Small/medium heap (&lt; 16GB):</strong><br>G1GC is efficient and well-tuned for this range.<br><br><strong>3. Throughput matters more than latency:</strong><br>Batch processing, background jobs → G1GC's higher throughput is better.<br><br><strong>4. Limited CPU resources:</strong><br>ZGC uses more CPU for concurrent marking (trades CPU for lower latency).<br><br><strong>5. Java version &lt; 15:</strong><br>ZGC was experimental before Java 15. Stick with G1GC for stability.<br><br><strong>Example decision tree:</strong><br><pre>Is p99 latency SLO &lt; 10ms?\n├─ YES → Consider ZGC\n│  └─ Is heap &gt; 16GB?\n│     ├─ YES → Use ZGC\n│     └─ NO → Try G1GC first, switch if pauses too high\n└─ NO → Use G1GC</pre><br><strong>Configuration comparison:</strong><br><br><strong>G1GC:</strong><br><pre>-XX:+UseG1GC\n-Xms8g -Xmx8g\n-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=20\n-XX:G1HeapRegionSize=16m</pre><br><strong>ZGC:</strong><br><pre>-XX:+UseZGC\n-Xms16g -Xmx16g\n# No pause time tuning needed (auto &lt; 1ms)</pre><br><strong>Real-world example:</strong><br>A payment service with 100GB heap, p99 latency SLO &lt; 10ms:<ul><li>G1GC: struggled with 50-100ms pauses → SLO violations</li><li>ZGC: consistent &lt; 1ms pauses → SLO met, fewer incidents</li></ul><br><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Start with G1GC. Only switch to ZGC if you have proven latency issues or very large heaps."},

    {q:"What tools would you use to profile CPU hotspots in a production Java application?",d:"medium",
     a:"Profiling in production requires low-overhead tools that don't significantly impact performance.<br><br><strong>1. async-profiler (Recommended for production):</strong><br><strong>Best all-around profiler</strong> — low overhead (~1%), works in production.<ul><li>Uses Linux perf events (no safepoints needed)</li><li>Generates flame graphs (visual CPU hotspots)</li><li>Profiles CPU, allocations, locks</li></ul><br><pre># Download from github.com/jvm-profiling-tools/async-profiler\n# Profile for 60 seconds\n./profiler.sh -d 60 -f /tmp/flamegraph.html &lt;pid&gt;\n\n# CPU profiling\n./profiler.sh -e cpu -d 60 -f cpu.html &lt;pid&gt;\n\n# Allocation profiling\n./profiler.sh -e alloc -d 60 -f alloc.html &lt;pid&gt;</pre><br><strong>Flame graph interpretation:</strong><ul><li>Width = time spent (wider = hotter)</li><li>Height = call stack depth</li><li>Look for wide plateaus at the top (hotspots)</li></ul><br><strong>2. Java Flight Recorder (JFR) — JDK built-in:</strong><br>Low overhead (&lt; 1%), production-safe, built into JDK 11+.<pre># Start recording\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.start duration=60s filename=/tmp/recording.jfr\n\n# Check status\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.check\n\n# Dump early (if needed)\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.dump filename=/tmp/dump.jfr</pre><br><strong>Analyze with JDK Mission Control (JMC):</strong><br>Download from jdk.java.net/jmc/<ul><li>CPU profiling tab shows hot methods</li><li>Memory profiling shows allocation hotspots</li><li>GC analysis, thread contention, I/O</li></ul><br><strong>Enable JFR at startup:</strong><br><pre>-XX:StartFlightRecording=duration=60s,filename=/tmp/recording.jfr</pre><br><strong>3. jstack (Thread dumps for stuck threads):</strong><br>Zero overhead, quick snapshot of all threads.<pre>jstack &lt;pid&gt; &gt; thread-dump.txt\n\n# Take 3 dumps 10 seconds apart\njstack &lt;pid&gt; &gt; dump1.txt; sleep 10\njstack &lt;pid&gt; &gt; dump2.txt; sleep 10\njstack &lt;pid&gt; &gt; dump3.txt</pre>Compare dumps:<ul><li>Threads stuck in the same method = CPU hotspot or deadlock</li><li>Look for <code>RUNNABLE</code> threads consuming CPU</li></ul><br><strong>4. perf (Linux profiler):</strong><br>Low-level CPU profiling, kernel + JVM.<pre># Profile for 60s\nperf record -F 99 -p &lt;pid&gt; -g -- sleep 60\nperf script &gt; out.perf\n\n# Generate flame graph\ngit clone https://github.com/brendangregg/FlameGraph\nperf script | ./FlameGraph/stackcollapse-perf.pl | ./FlameGraph/flamegraph.pl &gt; flame.svg</pre><br><strong>5. VisualVM (attach to running process):</strong><br>GUI tool, but higher overhead (5-10%) — use in staging, not prod.<ul><li>CPU sampler (low overhead)</li><li>Memory sampler</li><li>Thread viewer</li></ul><pre># Launch\njvisualvm\n# Attach to PID → Sampler tab → CPU</pre><br><strong>6. APM tools (Datadog, New Relic, Dynatrace):</strong><br>Always-on profiling with low overhead.<ul><li>Datadog Continuous Profiler: flame graphs in UI</li><li>New Relic Thread Profiler</li><li>Dynatrace PurePath (code-level traces)</li></ul><br><strong>Enable Datadog profiler:</strong><br><pre>-Ddd.profiling.enabled=true\n-Ddd.profiling.api-key-file=/etc/datadog/api-key</pre><br><br><strong>Comparison:</strong><br><table><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Overhead</th><th>Use Case</th></tr><tr><td>async-profiler</td><td>~1%</td><td>Production CPU hotspots</td></tr><tr><td>JFR</td><td>&lt;1%</td><td>Production, comprehensive</td></tr><tr><td>jstack</td><td>0%</td><td>Quick stuck thread analysis</td></tr><tr><td>perf</td><td>~1%</td><td>Kernel + JVM profiling</td></tr><tr><td>VisualVM</td><td>5-10%</td><td>Staging/development</td></tr><tr><td>APM</td><td>1-3%</td><td>Always-on prod monitoring</td></tr></table><br><strong>Production profiling checklist:</strong><ol><li>Start with JFR or async-profiler (low overhead)</li><li>Profile for 60-120 seconds (enough samples)</li><li>Analyze flame graphs for wide plateaus</li><li>Focus on application code hotspots (ignore JDK internals unless suspicious)</li><li>Validate findings with a second profiling run</li></ol>"},

    {q:"How do you analyze a thread dump to identify deadlocks or thread starvation?",d:"hard",
     a:"<strong>Thread dumps</strong> are snapshots of all threads, showing their state and stack traces. Essential for debugging concurrency issues.<br><br><strong>Capturing a thread dump:</strong><br><pre># Method 1: jstack\njstack &lt;pid&gt; &gt; thread-dump.txt\n\n# Method 2: kill signal (on Linux)\nkill -3 &lt;pid&gt;  # dumps to stdout/log\n\n# Method 3: JMX\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; Thread.print &gt; thread-dump.txt</pre><br><strong>Take multiple dumps (10s apart) to see if threads are stuck.</strong><br><br><strong>Thread dump structure:</strong><br><pre>\"http-nio-8080-exec-42\" #84 daemon prio=5 tid=0x00007f8b2c3e4000 nid=0x4f2a waiting on condition\n   java.lang.Thread.State: WAITING (parking)\n   at sun.misc.Unsafe.park(Native Method)\n   at java.util.concurrent.locks.LockSupport.park()\n   at com.example.OrderService.processOrder(OrderService.java:45)\n   - locked &lt;0x00000007ffe12340&gt; (a java.lang.Object)</pre><br><br><strong>1. Identifying Deadlocks:</strong><br>jstack auto-detects deadlocks and prints a summary:<pre>Found one Java-level deadlock:\n=============================\n\"Thread-1\":\n  waiting to lock monitor 0x00007f9c1c004e00 (object 0x000000076ab0d8e8, a java.lang.Object),\n  which is held by \"Thread-2\"\n\"Thread-2\":\n  waiting to lock monitor 0x00007f9c1c006c00 (object 0x000000076ab0d8f8, a java.lang.Object),\n  which is held by \"Thread-1\"</pre><br><strong>Classic deadlock pattern:</strong><br><pre>// Thread 1\nsynchronized(lockA) {\n  synchronized(lockB) { ... }  // waiting for lockB\n}\n\n// Thread 2\nsynchronized(lockB) {\n  synchronized(lockA) { ... }  // waiting for lockA\n}</pre><br><strong>Solution:</strong> always acquire locks in the same order.<br><br><strong>2. Identifying Blocked Threads:</strong><br>Look for threads in <code>BLOCKED</code> state:<pre>\"http-nio-8080-exec-15\" #45 waiting for monitor entry\n   java.lang.Thread.State: BLOCKED (on object monitor)\n   at com.example.OrderService.processOrder(OrderService.java:45)\n   - waiting to lock &lt;0x00000007ffe12340&gt; (a java.lang.Object)\n   - locked by \"http-nio-8080-exec-12\" #42</pre><br><strong>Indicates:</strong> lock contention — many threads waiting for the same lock.<br><br><strong>Find the lock holder:</strong><br>Search for <code>locked &lt;0x00000007ffe12340&gt;</code> to see which thread holds it.<br><br><strong>3. Thread Starvation (threads waiting for work):</strong><br>Threads stuck in <code>WAITING</code> or <code>TIMED_WAITING</code>:<pre>\"http-nio-8080-exec-25\" #85 daemon waiting on condition\n   java.lang.Thread.State: TIMED_WAITING (parking)\n   at sun.misc.Unsafe.park(Native Method)\n   at java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor$Worker.run()</pre><br><strong>Indicates:</strong> thread pool idle or waiting for tasks.<br><br><strong>Thread pool exhaustion:</strong><br>If all threads are WAITING and requests are queued:<pre># All 200 threads in pool are busy:\n\"http-nio-8080-exec-1\" ... RUNNABLE ... at com.example.SlowService.call()\n\"http-nio-8080-exec-2\" ... RUNNABLE ... at com.example.SlowService.call()\n...\n\"http-nio-8080-exec-200\" ... RUNNABLE ... at com.example.SlowService.call()</pre><br><strong>Solution:</strong> increase thread pool size or optimize slow code.<br><br><strong>4. CPU-bound threads (hot threads):</strong><br>Threads in <code>RUNNABLE</code> state consuming CPU:<pre>\"compute-worker-5\" #92 runnable\n   java.lang.Thread.State: RUNNABLE\n   at com.example.Algorithm.compute(Algorithm.java:78)\n   at com.example.Algorithm.compute(Algorithm.java:65)  # recursive\n   at com.example.Algorithm.compute(Algorithm.java:65)</pre><br><strong>Indicates:</strong> CPU-intensive work or infinite loop.<br><br><strong>5. Threads stuck in I/O:</strong><br><pre>\"db-connection-waiter\" #55 runnable\n   java.lang.Thread.State: RUNNABLE\n   at java.net.SocketInputStream.socketRead0(Native Method)\n   at com.mysql.jdbc.MysqlIO.readFully()</pre><br><strong>Indicates:</strong> waiting for slow I/O (database, network).<br><br><strong>6. Analyzing multiple dumps:</strong><br>Compare 3 dumps taken 10s apart:<ul><li>If a thread shows the <em>same stack trace</em> in all 3 dumps → stuck</li><li>If stack traces differ → thread is making progress</li></ul><br><strong>Tools for analysis:</strong><br><br><strong>fastthread.io (online analyzer):</strong><br>Upload dump → auto-detects deadlocks, blocked threads, hot threads<br><br><strong>TDA (Thread Dump Analyzer):</strong><br>Java GUI tool, visualizes thread states<br><br><strong>grep shortcuts:</strong><br><pre># Count threads by state\ngrep \"java.lang.Thread.State\" thread-dump.txt | sort | uniq -c\n\n# Find deadlocks\ngrep -A 20 \"deadlock\" thread-dump.txt\n\n# Find blocked threads\ngrep -B 5 \"BLOCKED\" thread-dump.txt</pre><br><strong>Common issues and fixes:</strong><br><table><tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Cause</th><th>Fix</th></tr><tr><td>Deadlock detected</td><td>Circular lock dependency</td><td>Reorder lock acquisition</td></tr><tr><td>Many BLOCKED threads</td><td>Lock contention</td><td>Reduce synchronized scope, use concurrent collections</td></tr><tr><td>All threads WAITING</td><td>No work available</td><td>Check upstream queue/producer</td></tr><tr><td>All threads RUNNABLE in same method</td><td>CPU bottleneck</td><td>Optimize algorithm, add caching</td></tr><tr><td>Threads stuck in I/O</td><td>Slow database/network</td><td>Add timeouts, optimize query</td></tr></table>"},

    {q:"What are the key JVM flags for tuning a production Spring Boot application?",d:"medium",
     a:"These are battle-tested JVM flags for production Spring Boot microservices.<br><br><strong>Essential flags (always set):</strong><br><pre># Heap size (set equal to avoid resizing)\n-Xms4g -Xmx4g\n\n# Use G1GC (default since Java 9, but explicit is clear)\n-XX:+UseG1GC\n\n# GC logging (essential for debugging)\n-Xlog:gc*:file=/var/log/gc.log:time,level,tags:filecount=5,filesize=100M\n\n# Heap dump on OOM (for post-mortem analysis)\n-XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError\n-XX:HeapDumpPath=/var/log/heapdumps/\n\n# Exit on OOM (let orchestrator restart)\n-XX:+ExitOnOutOfMemoryError</pre><br><strong>G1GC tuning (low-latency microservices):</strong><br><pre># Target max GC pause time\n-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200  # aim for 200ms (default is 200, adjust as needed)\n\n# Number of GC threads (default is CPU cores / 4)\n-XX:ParallelGCThreads=4\n\n# Concurrent GC threads\n-XX:ConcGCThreads=1\n\n# Initiate marking cycle earlier (if you see long pauses)\n-XX:InitiatingHeapOccupancyPercent=45  # default 45%</pre><br><strong>ZGC (ultra-low latency, Java 15+):</strong><br><pre>-XX:+UseZGC\n-Xms16g -Xmx16g\n# ZGC has minimal tuning (mostly auto)</pre><br><strong>Memory and metaspace:</strong><br><pre># Metaspace (class metadata, not in heap)\n-XX:MetaspaceSize=256m\n-XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m\n\n# String deduplication (saves memory for duplicate strings)\n-XX:+UseStringDeduplication  # G1GC only\n\n# Compressed pointers (automatic &lt; 32GB heap)\n-XX:+UseCompressedOops  # default on</pre><br><strong>Performance flags:</strong><br><pre># Tiered compilation (default on, but explicit)\n-XX:+TieredCompilation\n-XX:TieredStopAtLevel=1  # C1 only (faster startup, lower throughput)\n                         # Use for short-lived containers\n\n# Large pages (if OS supports, reduces TLB misses)\n-XX:+UseLargePages\n\n# Biased locking (deprecated in Java 15+, removed in 18)\n# Don't use: -XX:-UseBiasedLocking</pre><br><strong>Diagnostic and monitoring:</strong><br><pre># Enable JMX (for monitoring tools)\n-Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote\n-Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.port=9010\n-Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.authenticate=false\n-Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.ssl=false\n\n# Enable JFR (low-overhead profiling)\n-XX:+FlightRecorder\n\n# Print JVM flags on startup (for verification)\n-XX:+PrintFlagsFinal  # logs all flags</pre><br><strong>Container-aware settings (Docker/Kubernetes):</strong><br><pre># Respect container memory limits (Java 10+)\n-XX:+UseContainerSupport  # default on\n\n# Max RAM percentage (use 75% of container memory for heap)\n-XX:MaxRAMPercentage=75.0\n\n# Example: 4GB container → 3GB heap\n# No need for -Xms/-Xmx if using MaxRAMPercentage</pre><br><strong>Complete example — 4GB heap, low-latency API:</strong><br><pre>java \\\n  -Xms4g -Xmx4g \\\n  -XX:+UseG1GC \\\n  -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=100 \\\n  -XX:+UseStringDeduplication \\\n  -Xlog:gc*:file=/var/log/gc.log:time,level,tags \\\n  -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError \\\n  -XX:HeapDumpPath=/var/log/heapdumps/ \\\n  -XX:+ExitOnOutOfMemoryError \\\n  -XX:MetaspaceSize=256m \\\n  -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m \\\n  -jar app.jar</pre><br><strong>Complete example — Kubernetes with container limits:</strong><br><pre>resources:\n  limits:\n    memory: 4Gi\n  requests:\n    memory: 4Gi\n\n# JVM flags\njava \\\n  -XX:MaxRAMPercentage=75.0 \\\n  -XX:+UseG1GC \\\n  -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=100 \\\n  -Xlog:gc*:file=/var/log/gc.log:time,level,tags \\\n  -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError \\\n  -XX:HeapDumpPath=/var/log/heapdumps/ \\\n  -jar app.jar</pre><br><strong>What NOT to do:</strong><ul><li>❌ Don't set <code>-Xms != -Xmx</code> (heap resizing causes pauses)</li><li>❌ Don't set <code>MaxGCPauseMillis</code> too low (&lt; 50ms unrealistic for G1)</li><li>❌ Don't disable GC logging (you'll regret it during incidents)</li><li>❌ Don't use Serial GC (<code>-XX:+UseSerialGC</code>) in production</li><li>❌ Don't set heap &gt; 32GB without testing (compressed oops disabled)</li></ul>"},

    {q:"How do you use Java Flight Recorder (JFR) to diagnose performance issues?",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>Java Flight Recorder (JFR)</strong> is a low-overhead (&lt; 1%) profiling and diagnostic tool built into the JDK (since Java 11).<br><br><strong>What JFR captures:</strong><ul><li>CPU profiling (hot methods)</li><li>Object allocation (memory hotspots)</li><li>GC events (pause times, heap usage)</li><li>Thread activity (locks, sleeps, I/O)</li><li>JIT compilation events</li><li>Exceptions thrown</li><li>File and network I/O</li></ul><br><br><strong>Starting a recording:</strong><br><br><strong>Method 1 — Command line (runtime):</strong><br><pre># Start 60-second recording\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.start duration=60s filename=/tmp/recording.jfr\n\n# Check recording status\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.check\n\n# Stop and dump early\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.dump filename=/tmp/dump.jfr\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.stop</pre><br><strong>Method 2 — JVM startup flag:</strong><br><pre>java -XX:StartFlightRecording=duration=60s,filename=/tmp/recording.jfr -jar app.jar</pre><br><strong>Method 3 — Continuous recording (recommended for production):</strong><br><pre># Keep last 6 hours of data in circular buffer\njava -XX:StartFlightRecording=name=continuous,maxage=6h,disk=true -jar app.jar\n\n# Dump on-demand when issue occurs\njcmd &lt;pid&gt; JFR.dump name=continuous filename=/tmp/incident.jfr</pre><br><br><strong>Analyzing with JDK Mission Control (JMC):</strong><br><br><strong>Download JMC:</strong> jdk.java.net/jmc/<br><br><strong>Open recording.jfr in JMC:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Automated Analysis:</strong><br>JMC auto-detects issues and scores them:<ul><li>High GC pressure (90/100 = severe)</li><li>Lock contention detected</li><li>Frequent exceptions</li><li>Large object allocations</li></ul><br><strong>2. Method Profiling tab:</strong><br>Shows CPU hotspots:<pre>Method                           | Samples | %\n---------------------------------|---------|------\ncom.example.OrderService.process | 1,245   | 42%\njava.util.HashMap.get            | 320     | 11%\ncom.example.PaymentClient.call  | 280     | 9%</pre>Focus on application code consuming &gt; 10% CPU.<br><br><strong>3. Memory tab (allocation profiling):</strong><br>Shows which methods allocate the most objects:<pre>Method                           | Allocations | Size\n---------------------------------|-------------|----------\ncom.example.Report.generate      | 5.2M        | 420 MB\ncom.example.QueryBuilder.build   | 2.1M        | 180 MB</pre>Optimize high-allocation code paths.<br><br><strong>4. GC tab:</strong><ul><li>Longest GC pause: 250ms (at 14:32:15)</li><li>Total GC time: 5.2% (good if &lt; 10%)</li><li>Heap after GC: trending up (potential leak)</li></ul><br><strong>5. Threads tab:</strong><ul><li>Lock contention: 15% of time spent waiting for locks</li><li>Java monitors: <code>OrderService.lock</code> contended 1,200 times</li><li>Deadlocks detected: none</li></ul><br><strong>6. Exceptions tab:</strong><br>Shows exception counts and stack traces:<pre>Exception                        | Count\n---------------------------------|-------\nNullPointerException             | 1,245\nNumberFormatException            | 87</pre><br><strong>7. I/O tab:</strong><ul><li>File reads: 12,000 (avg 5ms each)</li><li>Socket reads: 450,000 (avg 12ms each)</li></ul>Identify slow I/O operations.<br><br><strong>Common performance issues found with JFR:</strong><br><br><strong>Issue 1 — High CPU in a method:</strong><br><pre>Method Profiling → com.example.Algorithm.compute 65% CPU</pre>Solution: profile locally, optimize algorithm<br><br><strong>Issue 2 — Memory allocation hotspot:</strong><br><pre>Memory → com.example.Report.generate allocates 500MB/sec</pre>Solution: reuse objects, use StringBuilder<br><br><strong>Issue 3 — Lock contention:</strong><br><pre>Threads → Java Monitor blocked 40% of the time on CacheManager.lock</pre>Solution: use ConcurrentHashMap instead of synchronized<br><br><strong>Issue 4 — Frequent GC:</strong><br><pre>GC → 15% time in GC, heap filling up quickly</pre>Solution: reduce allocations, increase heap, tune GC<br><br><strong>JFR in Kubernetes:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: v1\nkind: Pod\nspec:\n  containers:\n  - name: app\n    command:\n    - java\n    - -XX:StartFlightRecording=maxage=6h,disk=true\n    - -jar\n    - app.jar\n    volumeMounts:\n    - name: jfr-data\n      mountPath: /var/jfr\n  volumes:\n  - name: jfr-data\n    emptyDir: {}</pre><br>Extract recording:<br><pre>kubectl exec &lt;pod&gt; -- jcmd 1 JFR.dump filename=/var/jfr/recording.jfr\nkubectl cp &lt;pod&gt;:/var/jfr/recording.jfr ./recording.jfr</pre><br><strong>Alternatives to JFR:</strong><ul><li><strong>async-profiler:</strong> better CPU profiling, flame graphs</li><li><strong>APM tools:</strong> Datadog, New Relic (always-on, lower detail)</li></ul><br><strong>Best practice:</strong> Enable continuous JFR (maxage=6h) in production. Dump on incidents."},

    {q:"What causes stop-the-world (STW) pauses and how do you minimize them?",d:"hard",
     a:"<strong>Stop-the-world (STW) pauses</strong> occur when all application threads are paused so the JVM can perform GC or other VM operations.<br><br><strong>What causes STW pauses:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Garbage Collection (most common):</strong><ul><li><strong>Young GC:</strong> typically 10-50ms (acceptable)</li><li><strong>Full GC:</strong> can be 100ms - 10s (problematic)</li><li>Frequency depends on allocation rate and heap size</li></ul><br><strong>2. JVM internal operations:</strong><ul><li><strong>Deoptimization:</strong> JIT compiler reverting optimized code (rare)</li><li><strong>Class redefinition:</strong> hot code reload (development only)</li><li><strong>Biased locking revocation:</strong> (deprecated in Java 15+)</li><li><strong>ThreadDump / Heap dump:</strong> <code>jstack</code>, <code>jmap</code> pause the app</li></ul><br><strong>3. Safepoints:</strong><br>JVM brings all threads to a <em>safepoint</em> before STW operations. Long time-to-safepoint (TTSP) can delay GC.<br><br><br><strong>Minimizing STW pauses:</strong><br><br><strong>Strategy 1 — Use a low-latency GC:</strong><br><br><strong>G1GC (balanced):</strong><br><pre>-XX:+UseG1GC\n-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=100  # target 100ms pauses</pre>Young GC: 10-50ms (STW, but short)<br>Mixed GC: 50-200ms (STW, more work)<br>Full GC: rare if tuned well<br><br><strong>ZGC (ultra-low latency, Java 15+):</strong><br><pre>-XX:+UseZGC\n-Xms16g -Xmx16g</pre>All phases concurrent except brief pauses (&lt; 1ms):<ul><li>Pause Mark Start: &lt; 1ms</li><li>Pause Mark End: &lt; 1ms</li><li>Pause Relocate Start: &lt; 1ms</li></ul><br><strong>Shenandoah (similar to ZGC):</strong><br><pre>-XX:+UseShenandoahGC</pre><br><br><strong>Strategy 2 — Reduce GC frequency:</strong><br><br><strong>Increase heap size:</strong><br><pre># More heap = less frequent GC\n-Xms8g -Xmx8g  # instead of 4g</pre>But: larger heap = longer GC pauses (trade-off)<br><br><strong>Reduce allocation rate:</strong><ul><li>Reuse objects (object pooling for hot paths)</li><li>Avoid creating temporary objects in loops</li><li>Use primitive types instead of boxed types</li></ul><br><pre>// Bad: allocates Integer objects\nfor (int i = 0; i &lt; 1000000; i++) {\n  list.add(Integer.valueOf(i));\n}\n\n// Good: primitive int array\nint[] arr = new int[1000000];</pre><br><br><strong>Strategy 3 — Tune GC for your workload:</strong><br><br><strong>For G1GC:</strong><br><pre># Increase young gen size (fewer young GCs)\n-XX:G1NewSizePercent=30  # default 5%\n-XX:G1MaxNewSizePercent=60  # default 60%\n\n# Adjust region size (for large objects)\n-XX:G1HeapRegionSize=16m  # default: heap_size / 2048\n\n# More aggressive marking (prevent full GC)\n-XX:InitiatingHeapOccupancyPercent=45  # default 45%</pre><br><br><strong>Strategy 4 — Eliminate full GCs:</strong><br>Full GCs are the worst (100ms - 10s pauses).<br><br><strong>Causes of full GC:</strong><ol><li><strong>Heap exhaustion:</strong> not enough space for objects<br>   Fix: increase heap, reduce allocations</li><li><strong>Metaspace full:</strong><br>   Fix: <code>-XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m</code></li><li><strong>Explicit <code>System.gc()</code>:</strong><br>   Fix: <code>-XX:+DisableExplicitGC</code></li><li><strong>Humongous objects (G1GC):</strong> objects &gt; 50% of region size trigger full GC<br>   Fix: increase region size: <code>-XX:G1HeapRegionSize=32m</code></li></ol><br><br><strong>Strategy 5 — Reduce time-to-safepoint (TTSP):</strong><br>Long TTSP = threads take long to reach safepoint.<br><br><strong>Common causes:</strong><ul><li>Counted loops without safepoint checks</li><li>Long-running JNI calls</li></ul><br><pre>// Bad: long loop without safepoint checks\nfor (int i = 0; i &lt; 1_000_000_000; i++) {\n  sum += i;\n}\n\n// Good: add safepoint polling\nfor (int i = 0; i &lt; 1_000_000_000; i++) {\n  sum += i;\n  if (i % 10000 == 0) Thread.onSpinWait();  // safepoint opportunity\n}</pre><br><strong>Enable safepoint logging:</strong><br><pre>-Xlog:safepoint</pre>Look for long TTSP in logs.<br><br><br><strong>Strategy 6 — Avoid heap dumps in production:</strong><br><code>jmap -dump</code> causes a full STW pause (seconds to minutes).<br><br>Instead:<ul><li>Enable auto heap dumps on OOM: <code>-XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError</code></li><li>Use JFR for allocation profiling (no STW)</li></ul><br><br><strong>Monitoring STW pauses:</strong><br><br><strong>1. GC logs:</strong><br><pre>-Xlog:gc*:file=/var/log/gc.log:time,level,tags</pre>Parse logs:<pre>[2024-04-08T14:32:15.123] GC(45) Pause Young (Normal) 125ms</pre><br><strong>2. JFR:</strong><br>Captures GC pauses with histogram.<br><br><strong>3. Prometheus + Micrometer:</strong><br><pre>jvm_gc_pause_seconds_count\njvm_gc_pause_seconds_sum</pre><br><strong>4. APM tools:</strong><br>Datadog, New Relic show GC pause times in dashboards.<br><br><strong>Summary:</strong><br><table><tr><th>Workload</th><th>GC Choice</th><th>Expected Pause</th></tr><tr><td>Batch jobs</td><td>Parallel GC</td><td>100ms - 1s (acceptable)</td></tr><tr><td>Web APIs</td><td>G1GC</td><td>10-50ms</td></tr><tr><td>Real-time</td><td>ZGC</td><td>&lt; 1ms</td></tr></table>"},

    {q:"How do you detect and fix a cache line false sharing issue?",d:"hard",
     a:"<strong>False sharing</strong> occurs when threads on different CPU cores modify variables on the same cache line, causing excessive cache invalidation and performance degradation.<br><br><strong>What is a cache line?</strong><ul><li>CPU caches data in 64-byte chunks (cache lines)</li><li>If two threads modify different variables on the same cache line, the entire line is invalidated across cores</li><li>Result: constant cache misses, dramatically slower performance (10x+)</li></ul><br><strong>Example of false sharing:</strong><br><pre>class Counter {\n  volatile long counterA;  // offset 0\n  volatile long counterB;  // offset 8 (same cache line!)\n}\n\n// Thread 1: constantly updates counterA\ncounterA++;\n\n// Thread 2: constantly updates counterB\ncounterB++;</pre>Both counters are on the same 64-byte cache line → false sharing.<br><br><br><strong>Detecting false sharing:</strong><br><br><strong>Method 1 — Performance symptoms:</strong><ul><li>Multi-threaded code slower than expected</li><li>Performance doesn't scale with CPU cores</li><li>High CPU cache miss rate</li></ul><br><strong>Method 2 — CPU performance counters (perf):</strong><br><pre># Profile cache misses\nperf stat -e cache-misses,cache-references java -jar app.jar\n\n# High cache-misses/cache-references ratio = false sharing</pre><br><strong>Method 3 — Intel VTune or perf c2c (cache-to-cache):</strong><br><pre>perf c2c record java -jar app.jar\nperf c2c report</pre>Shows which cache lines have high contention.<br><br><strong>Method 4 — JMH microbenchmark:</strong><br><pre>@State(Scope.Group)\npublic class FalseSharingTest {\n  volatile long counterA;\n  volatile long counterB;\n\n  @Benchmark\n  @Group(\"g\")\n  public void incrementA() {\n    counterA++;\n  }\n\n  @Benchmark\n  @Group(\"g\")\n  public void incrementB() {\n    counterB++;\n  }\n}</pre>Run with 2 threads → compare throughput with/without padding.<br><br><br><strong>Fixing false sharing:</strong><br><br><strong>Solution 1 — Padding (manual):</strong><br>Add padding to separate variables into different cache lines:<br><pre>class Counter {\n  volatile long counterA;\n  long p1, p2, p3, p4, p5, p6, p7;  // 56 bytes padding\n  volatile long counterB;           // now on different cache line\n}</pre><br><strong>Why 7 longs?</strong><br><code>long</code> = 8 bytes × 7 = 56 bytes<br><code>counterA</code> (8 bytes) + padding (56 bytes) = 64 bytes = 1 cache line<br><br><strong>Solution 2 — @Contended annotation (Java 8+):</strong><br>JVM automatically adds padding:<br><pre>import jdk.internal.vm.annotation.Contended;\n\nclass Counter {\n  @Contended\n  volatile long counterA;\n  \n  @Contended\n  volatile long counterB;\n}</pre><br><strong>Enable @Contended:</strong><br><pre>-XX:-RestrictContended  # allows @Contended in user code</pre><br><strong>Solution 3 — Separate objects:</strong><br>Put each counter in its own object:<br><pre>class CounterHolder {\n  volatile long value;\n}\n\nCounterHolder holderA = new CounterHolder();\nCounterHolder holderB = new CounterHolder();</pre>JVM allocates objects with spacing, avoiding false sharing.<br><br><strong>Solution 4 — Use Striped64 / LongAdder:</strong><br>For counters, use <code>LongAdder</code> (designed to avoid false sharing):<br><pre>// Instead of volatile long\nLongAdder counterA = new LongAdder();\nLongAdder counterB = new LongAdder();\n\n// Thread-safe, no false sharing\ncounterA.increment();\ncounterB.increment();</pre><br><br><strong>Real-world example — JDK's LongAdder:</strong><br><code>LongAdder</code> internally uses padding to avoid false sharing:<br><pre>// Simplified LongAdder internals\nstatic final class Cell {\n  @Contended\n  volatile long value;\n}</pre><br><br><strong>When to worry about false sharing:</strong><ul><li>High-contention, multi-threaded code</li><li>Per-thread counters or statistics</li><li>Lock-free data structures</li><li>Performance-critical loops with thread-local variables</li></ul><br><strong>When NOT to worry:</strong><ul><li>Low-contention code</li><li>Single-threaded applications</li><li>I/O-bound workloads (false sharing is negligible)</li></ul><br><br><strong>Verification with JMH:</strong><br><pre>@State(Scope.Group)\npublic class Benchmark {\n  // Before: false sharing\n  volatile long counterA;\n  volatile long counterB;\n  \n  // After: padding\n  @Contended volatile long counterAPadded;\n  @Contended volatile long counterBPadded;\n}\n\nResult (ops/sec):\nBefore: 12M ops/sec\nAfter:  85M ops/sec  # 7x faster!</pre><br><br><strong>Summary:</strong><ul><li>False sharing = invisible performance killer in multi-threaded code</li><li>Symptoms: poor scaling, high cache misses</li><li>Fix: <code>@Contended</code>, manual padding, or <code>LongAdder</code></li><li>Always benchmark before/after to confirm improvement</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is escape analysis and how does it optimize object allocation?",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>Escape analysis</strong> is a JIT compiler optimization that determines if an object's lifetime is confined to a method. If so, the JVM can optimize allocation.<br><br><strong>What is \"escaping\"?</strong><br>An object <em>escapes</em> if:<ul><li>It's assigned to a field (heap)</li><li>It's returned from the method</li><li>It's passed to another method that lets it escape</li></ul><br>An object <em>doesn't escape</em> if:<ul><li>It's only used within the method (local scope)</li><li>It doesn't outlive the method</li></ul><br><br><strong>Example — Object that escapes:</strong><br><pre>public User createUser(String name) {\n  User user = new User(name);  // allocated on heap\n  return user;                 // escapes (returned)\n}</pre><br><strong>Example — Object that doesn't escape:</strong><br><pre>public int computeTotal() {\n  Point p = new Point(10, 20);  // only used locally\n  return p.x + p.y;             // doesn't escape\n}</pre><br><br><strong>Optimizations enabled by escape analysis:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Stack allocation (scalar replacement):</strong><br>Instead of allocating on the heap, the JVM can allocate on the stack or eliminate the object entirely.<br><pre>// Before optimization (heap allocation)\npublic int computeTotal() {\n  Point p = new Point(10, 20);  // heap allocation\n  return p.x + p.y;\n}\n\n// After optimization (scalar replacement)\npublic int computeTotal() {\n  int x = 10;  // local variables on stack\n  int y = 20;\n  return x + y;  // no object created!\n}</pre><br><strong>Benefits:</strong><ul><li>No heap allocation → no GC pressure</li><li>Faster (stack allocation is cheaper)</li></ul><br><strong>2. Lock elision:</strong><br>If a synchronized object doesn't escape, the JVM can remove the lock.<pre>// Before optimization\npublic void process() {\n  StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();  // doesn't escape\n  sb.append(\"hello\");  // synchronized method\n  sb.append(\" world\");\n  System.out.println(sb.toString());\n}\n\n// After optimization (lock removed)\npublic void process() {\n  StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();\n  sb.append(\"hello\");  // no lock!\n  sb.append(\" world\");\n  System.out.println(sb.toString());\n}</pre><br><strong>Why?</strong> <code>StringBuffer</code> is synchronized, but since <code>sb</code> doesn't escape, no other thread can access it → locks are unnecessary.<br><br><strong>3. Object elimination:</strong><br>If an object is only used for intermediate calculations, the JVM can eliminate it entirely.<br><br><br><strong>How to enable escape analysis:</strong><br><pre># Enabled by default in JDK 6u23+\n-XX:+DoEscapeAnalysis  # default on\n\n# Disable (for testing)\n-XX:-DoEscapeAnalysis</pre><br><br><strong>Checking if escape analysis is working:</strong><br><br><strong>Method 1 — Print compilation logs:</strong><br><pre>-XX:+UnlockDiagnosticVMOptions\n-XX:+PrintEliminateAllocations\n-XX:+PrintEscapeAnalysis</pre>Shows which objects are eliminated.<br><br><strong>Method 2 — JMH benchmark:</strong><br><pre>@Benchmark\npublic int testEscapeAnalysis() {\n  Point p = new Point(10, 20);\n  return p.x + p.y;\n}\n\n// Run with/without escape analysis\n// With: 10ns per op (no allocation)\n// Without: 25ns per op (heap allocation + GC)</pre><br><br><strong>Method 3 — JFR allocation profiling:</strong><br>If escape analysis works, you won't see allocations for non-escaping objects.<br><br><br><strong>When escape analysis helps:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Builder pattern:</strong><br><pre>public String buildQuery(int id) {\n  StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();  // doesn't escape\n  sb.append(\"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id=\");\n  sb.append(id);\n  return sb.toString();  // only the String escapes\n}</pre><code>StringBuilder</code> allocation is eliminated.<br><br><strong>2. Temporary objects in loops:</strong><br><pre>for (int i = 0; i &lt; 1000; i++) {\n  Point p = new Point(i, i*2);  // doesn't escape\n  sum += p.x + p.y;\n}</pre>No heap allocations → faster, no GC pressure.<br><br><strong>3. Defensive copies:</strong><br><pre>public int process(User user) {\n  User copy = user.clone();  // doesn't escape\n  copy.setAge(30);\n  return copy.getAge();\n}</pre><br><br><strong>When escape analysis doesn't help:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Object escapes:</strong><br><pre>public User createUser() {\n  return new User();  // escapes (returned)\n}</pre><br><strong>2. Object stored in field:</strong><br><pre>private List&lt;User&gt; users = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n\npublic void addUser(String name) {\n  users.add(new User(name));  // escapes (stored in field)\n}</pre><br><strong>3. Passed to method that stores it:</strong><br><pre>public void process() {\n  User user = new User();\n  cache.put(\"key\", user);  // escapes (stored in cache)\n}</pre><br><br><strong>Limitations:</strong><ul><li>Only works for objects < 64 fields (heuristic limit)</li><li>JIT compiler must be able to inline the method</li><li>Complex call chains may prevent escape analysis</li></ul><br><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Keep objects local when possible</li><li>Use <code>StringBuilder</code> instead of <code>StringBuffer</code> (no synchronized overhead)</li><li>Avoid unnecessary object creation in hot loops</li><li>Trust the JIT — it's very good at escape analysis</li></ul>"},

    {q:"How do you configure and interpret HikariCP connection pool metrics?",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>HikariCP</strong> is the fastest and most reliable JDBC connection pool, and monitoring it is critical for database performance.<br><br><strong>Why monitor connection pools?</strong><ul><li>Pool exhaustion → requests wait → high latency</li><li>Connection leaks → pool fills up → eventual failure</li><li>Inefficient sizing → wasted resources or contention</li></ul><br><br><strong>Enabling HikariCP metrics (Spring Boot + Micrometer):</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-starter-actuator&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;\n&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;io.micrometer&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;micrometer-registry-prometheus&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;</pre><br><strong>application.properties:</strong><br><pre># Enable HikariCP metrics\nspring.datasource.hikari.pool-name=MyHikariPool\n\n# Connection pool sizing\nspring.datasource.hikari.maximum-pool-size=20\nspring.datasource.hikari.minimum-idle=5\nspring.datasource.hikari.connection-timeout=30000  # 30s\nspring.datasource.hikari.idle-timeout=600000       # 10min\nspring.datasource.hikari.max-lifetime=1800000      # 30min\n\n# Leak detection (warns if connection held &gt; 30s)\nspring.datasource.hikari.leak-detection-threshold=30000</pre><br><br><strong>Key HikariCP metrics (Prometheus):</strong><br><br><strong>1. Active connections:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_active{pool=\"MyHikariPool\"}</pre>Connections currently in use by the application.<br><br><strong>2. Idle connections:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_idle{pool=\"MyHikariPool\"}</pre>Connections available in the pool.<br><br><strong>3. Total connections:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections{pool=\"MyHikariPool\"}</pre>Active + idle = total connections in pool.<br><br><strong>4. Pending threads (waiting for connection):</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_pending{pool=\"MyHikariPool\"}</pre>Requests waiting for a connection → <strong>indicates pool exhaustion</strong>.<br><br><strong>5. Connection acquisition time:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_acquire_seconds{pool=\"MyHikariPool\",quantile=\"0.95\"}</pre>Time to acquire a connection. If &gt; 100ms, pool may be undersized.<br><br><strong>6. Connection usage time:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_usage_seconds{pool=\"MyHikariPool\",quantile=\"0.95\"}</pre>Time connections are held by the application. If very high → connection leaks.<br><br><strong>7. Connection creation time:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_creation_seconds{pool=\"MyHikariPool\",quantile=\"0.95\"}</pre>Time to create new connection to database. If high → database is slow or network latency.<br><br><strong>8. Timeout count:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_timeout_total{pool=\"MyHikariPool\"}</pre>Number of times connection acquisition timed out → <strong>indicates pool exhaustion</strong>.<br><br><br><strong>Grafana dashboard (example queries):</strong><br><br><strong>Active vs Total connections:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_active{pool=\"MyHikariPool\"}\nhikaricp_connections{pool=\"MyHikariPool\"}</pre>Graph shows how close you are to pool limit.<br><br><strong>Pool utilization (%):</strong><br><pre>(hikaricp_connections_active / hikaricp_connections) * 100</pre>If consistently &gt; 80%, increase pool size.<br><br><strong>Pending threads alert:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_pending &gt; 0</pre>Alert if requests are waiting for connections.<br><br><strong>Acquisition time p95:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_acquire_seconds{quantile=\"0.95\"}</pre>Should be &lt; 10ms. If &gt; 100ms → pool undersized.<br><br><br><strong>Interpreting metrics:</strong><br><br><strong>Problem 1 — Pool exhausted (pending &gt; 0):</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_active: 20 (at max)\nhikaricp_connections_pending: 15 (waiting)</pre><strong>Solution:</strong><ul><li>Increase <code>maximum-pool-size</code></li><li>Investigate slow queries (holding connections too long)</li><li>Check for connection leaks</li></ul><br><strong>Problem 2 — Connection leaks (usage time very high):</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_usage_seconds{quantile=\"0.95\"}: 300s  # 5 minutes!</pre><strong>Solution:</strong><ul><li>Enable leak detection: <code>leak-detection-threshold=30000</code></li><li>Check logs for warnings</li><li>Ensure connections are closed in <code>finally</code> blocks</li></ul><br><strong>Problem 3 — High acquisition time:</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_acquire_seconds{quantile=\"0.95\"}: 0.5s</pre><strong>Solution:</strong><ul><li>Pool is full → increase <code>maximum-pool-size</code></li><li>Database is slow → optimize queries</li></ul><br><strong>Problem 4 — Unused capacity (idle too high):</strong><br><pre>hikaricp_connections_active: 2\nhikaricp_connections_idle: 18  # 90% idle!</pre><strong>Solution:</strong><ul><li>Reduce <code>maximum-pool-size</code> (wasting resources)</li><li>Set <code>minimum-idle</code> lower</li></ul><br><br><strong>Right-sizing the pool:</strong><br><br><strong>Formula (rule of thumb):</strong><br><pre>connections = ((core_count * 2) + effective_spindle_count)</pre>Example: 4 cores, 1 disk → 9 connections<br><br><strong>But...</strong> it depends on workload:<ul><li><strong>I/O-bound (slow queries):</strong> larger pool (20-50)</li><li><strong>CPU-bound (fast queries):</strong> smaller pool (5-10)</li></ul><br><strong>Test and tune based on metrics!</strong><br><br><br><strong>Connection leak detection:</strong><br><pre>spring.datasource.hikari.leak-detection-threshold=30000</pre>Logs warning if connection held &gt; 30s:<pre>WARN: Connection leak detection triggered for connection held for 35000ms</pre><br><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Start with <code>maximum-pool-size=20</code>, tune based on metrics</li><li>Set <code>connection-timeout=30000</code> (fail fast if pool exhausted)</li><li>Enable leak detection in development</li><li>Monitor pending threads and acquisition time</li><li>Alert if pool utilization &gt; 80% for &gt; 5 minutes</li></ul>"}
  ]
